"""Cerebellar Resevoir Dynamics and COntext-Dependent Population Separation. 

This script implements a computaitonal simulation inspired by Rossert et al. 
to analyse recurrent resevoir dynamics and timing within the cerebellar cortex. 
It evaluates how subtle perturbations in context vectors alter recurrent network states
and drive high-dimensional population separation over time. 

Key Features: 
  - Inhibitory recurrent network simulation (N=1000 neurons) with synaptic decay. 
  - Context-dependent modulation (COntext A vs Context B) on time-series inputs. 
  - Metrics to calcualte Euclidean population distances and state trajectory separation. 
  - Graphical visualizations tracking mean firing rates, population distance 
    variablity, and activity diferentiation matrices. 

  Author: Tia Dhamrait
  Program: B.Sc Neuroscience, McMaster University
  Date: April 2026 

"""

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

np.random.seed(0) # fixes all randomness

